\begin{abstract}
Text-to-image diffusion models can produce unsafe content such as nudity, violence, and hate imagery, especially under adversarial prompts. Existing safety methods either fine-tune the weights, risking catastrophic forgetting, or apply blanket inference-time guidance that degrades benign generations. We propose \textbf{\ours{}}, a training-free concept-erasure framework driven by a small user-editable exemplar pack decomposed into $F$ semantic sub-categories. At each denoising step, a concept-alignment gate triggers a family-indexed dual text/image probe that partitions the unsafe region by pixel-wise winner-take-all, and a mask-gated correction modifies only the detected region in one of two complementary modes---anchor inpainting or hybrid guidance. Across four adversarial nudity benchmarks, four MJA categories, and multi-concept erasure, \ours{} substantially outperforms all training-free baselines while preserving COCO image quality. The framework transfers to SD~3 (MMDiT) and FLUX (DiT) without design changes.
\end{abstract}

